    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "description",
      "value": "Design and execute a systematic k-point convergence diagnostic for a defect supercell (e.g., oxygen vacancy in MgO) comparing pristine bulk vs. defective supercell convergence behavior across energy, forces, and band gap. The plan: (1) relax pristine bulk MgO at high k-grid, (2) create 2×2×2 supercell with a single O vacancy, (3) run SCF calculations at 6 k-point densities (Gamma-only, 2×2×2, 3×3×3, 4×4×4, 5×5×5, 6×6×6) for both pristine supercell and defective supercell, (4) extract total energy, forces on atoms near defect, and band gap at each k-density, (5) compute convergence curves and identify the k-density where each quantity stabilizes within 1 meV/atom, 1 meV/Å, and 0.05 eV respectively, (6) generate a diagnostic checklist figure showing the different convergence rates."
    },
    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "expected_prediction",
      "value": "The pristine supercell total energy will converge by 3×3×3 (ΔE < 1 meV/atom), while the defect formation energy will require 4×4×4 or denser (ΔE_form < 10 meV). Forces on the nearest-neighbor atoms to the vacancy will show the slowest convergence, requiring 5×5×5 to stabilize within 1 meV/Å. The band gap will converge faster for the pristine cell (3×3×3) than for the defective cell (4×4×4). The diagnostic checklist will reveal that the common practice of using the same k-grid for defect and pristine cells is insufficient — the defect cell needs at least one tier denser k-grid for force convergence."
    },
    {
